y it's economics we have the technology to make universal wireless coverage possible but it would be much too costly you could say we are getting the coverage we are paying for for the most part wireless phone coverage depends on the location and density number in an area of the antennas you see on buildings on towers and along highways those antennas or base stations connect each person's phone to the networks that can link it to any other phone in the world several physical constraints determine whether a phone gets coverage the first is spectrum wireless phone companies have paid billions of dollars to the federal government to lease a band of frequencies that they carve up into channels in each area for transmitting information between phones and base stations this is a limited resource a typical company's base station might make between 200 and 400 channels available companies have sophisticated techniques for transmitting multiple conversations at the same frequency but multiple access last modified thu 12 jan 2012 at 9 24 stay connected itunes icon google+ icon facebook icon twitter icon linkedin icon stanford university school of engineering 475 via ortega stanford california 94305 4121 650.725 1575 1997 2012 stanford university all rights reserved accreditation info terms of use copyright complaints contact us
